It prevents such situations:
```
@GetMapping(“/user/{id}”)
public User getUserById(@ParhVariable Long id) {
    id = 10L; // new value
    return userRepository.getById(id).orElse(null); // will response with wrong entity
}
```
In code above the program will NOT return the value, which user expected. And if you set `final` keyword on `id` variable and try to assign new value to `id` - the program will not even compile, which prevents not expected behavior in runtime. &lt;br&gt;

There is no strict rules always to use `final` or not - the most common approach is to use `final` when code is long and complicated.

Check also [this][1] answer.


