There are a lot of problems with your current approach, most fundamental of them is that an array is not the right data structure for parsing an arithmetic expression and evaluating arbitrary parts of it.

Even if you managed to do it correctly somehow, removing arbitrary elements from an  array is an `O(n)` operation, so this can become extremely slow.

As to your current code, the problem (ignoring the more fundamental ones), is that you change the structure of the array by removing an element, but still operate on it as if nothing had changed.
```
                list1.remove(i - 1);
                list1.remove(i);
                list1.remove(i+1);
```
When you remove element `i-1`, element `i` will be at index `i-1`, so removing `i` after that, is effectively removing the _old_ `i+1`, etc. This messes up your results and chances are high that you go out of bounds.

